<li>Castanie-Cornet , M.P. , Cam , K. , Bastiat , B. , Cros , A. , Bordes , P. and Gutierrez , C. ( 2010 ) Acid stress response in Escherichia coli : mechanism of regulation of gadA transcription by RcsB and GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24335284" target="_blank">24335284</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Finally , the presence of RcsB in the preparation of MBP-GadE puriﬁed from wild-type strain was conﬁrmed by western-blot analysis using antibody raised against RcsB ( kind provided by Anne Vianney ; data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of GadE and RcsB in complexes II and III was tested by using combinations of His-tagged and MBP-tagged versions of GadE and RcsB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>When GadE and RcsB were mixed in the presence of cross-linkers , the proﬁle observed was nearly the same as that obtained with RcsB alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , this strongly suggests that YhiE is involved in bacterial resistance to low pH and the protein was therefore renamed GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since gadC is required for acid resistance in pH 2.5 spent EG and GadE is required to induce gadC , the gadE mutant also died quickly under this condition ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17259322" target="_blank">17259322</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE , which activates these genes , was also required for high cell density-dependent acid resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17259322" target="_blank">17259322</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , genes outside the GadE regulon also contribute to resistance to extreme acid shock and are induced by mild pH shock ( 16 , 19 -- 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21571995" target="_blank">21571995</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was established that the RcsBD56E/GadE regulatory complex binds to the promoter regions of the two genes ( Figure 1A ) , demonstrating the direct control by the RcsB-P/GadE complex Identification of the targets directly controlled by HdfR or AdiY Real-time quantitative RT-PCR analysis showed that HdfR regulates aslB and gltBD , while AdiY regulates several genes involved in acid stress resistance ( adiA , adiC , aslB , gadA , gadBC , gltBD , hdeAB , hdeD and slp-dctR ) ( Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21034467" target="_blank">21034467</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although GadE controls its own targets gadE , gadW and gadX independently of RcsB ( Hommais et al. , 2004 ; Sayed et al. , 2007 ) , while RcsB regulates ﬂhDC and cps , independently of GadE ( Francez-Charlot et al. , 2003 ; Majdalani et al. , 2005 ) , the RcsB-P/GadE complex has its own regulon which includes gadA , gadBC , hdeAB , hdeD , slp-dctR , adiA , adiC , cadBA and gltBD ( Fig. 3 and Table 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>No effect of this mutation was observed ( Fig. 1a ) , indicating that the requirement for RcsB in acid resistance is not mediated by RcsA and that under these experimental conditions , the regulation of rcsA by GadE is not pertinent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>This demonstrates that GadE binds promoter regions of gadA , gadX , hdeD , which is involved in acid resistance , hdeAB , which encode chaperones , ompC , rcsA and rfaQ , which are involved in biosynthesis of the bacterial membrane , and gltBD , which is involved in the biosynthesis of glutamate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , GadE binds the gltBD promoter , suggesting a direct effect of this protein in the regulation of glutamate biosynthesis under acid conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with this interpretation , the abundance of transcripts encoding the acid-responsive regulators of gadA , gadBC , and hdeAB expression , GadE and GadX , decreased as aerobiosis increased ( Tables 3 and 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similarly , the complex regulation of the acid stress response gene gadA , which is activated by GadE and RcsB , involves repression by H-NS ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20952573" target="_blank">20952573</a>]<br></li>
<li>The gadA/BC genes , activated in response to acid stress and in stationary phase cells , are subjected to complex circuits of regulation involving 70 , S , cAMP receptor protein , H-NS , EvgAS , TorRS , GadE , GadX , GadW , and YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>These various features demonstrate that GadE is involved in the activation of this ﬁrst bacterial response to acid stress .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is acid induced and involved in acid induction of gadA/BC Fig. 6 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is also important to recognize that the relevance of this system extends beyond GDAR , since GadE is in fact a global regulator that activates numerous genes in addition to gadA/BC , and negatively regulates biofilm formation in K12 as well as epithelial attachment in enterohaemorrhagic E. coli ( EHEC ) ( Dahan et al. , 2004 ; Hommais et al. , 2004 ; Tatsuno et al. , 2003 ; J. W. Foster , unpublished observation ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>A GAD box resides upstream of the P1 promoter ( Ma et al. , 2003 ) ; therefore , increased GadE levels , which are attributable to the increase in T2 mRNA levels , may increase P1 promoter activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24600026" target="_blank">24600026</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is required to induce gadA and gadBC under all circumstances ( Ma et al. , 2003b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>RcsB-dependent regulation of gadABC is not mediated by the regulation of gadEWX genes The expression of gadA and gadBC is regulated by a complex network involving notably the GadE , GadW and GadX regulators ( Ma et al. , 2003 ; see Foster , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activation of gadA/B expression by GadE requires a GadE-binding box upstream of the promoter ( Castanié - Cornet & Foster , 2001 ; Ma et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>The GadE protein itself , which binds to three GAD box sequences present between '' 233 and '' 42 nt , helped activate GadE expression in LB , but only when the '' 798 to '' 360 region was absent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>The goal of the present study was to investigate the mechanism of regulation of the gad genes by GadE and RcsB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcription depends on rS and is positively regulated by GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is autoregulated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data presented in Fig. 4 indicate that GadE does help activate its own expression ( Fig. 4 , compare EF1244 and EF1247 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data further indicates that GadE activates itself and represses ydeO in a partial feedback loop .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this regulatory complex , GadE might be the limiting factor , as gadE gene expression is induced 10-fold in the hns-deﬁcient strain , while only RcsD-dependent phosphorylation of RcsB is affected .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genetic approaches had shown that in addition to the central regulator GadE , the response-regulator RcsB is strictly required to activate the expression of the three genes gadA/BC and to develop resistance to low pH ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>RESULTS The response-regulator RcsB is essential for glutamate-dependent acid resistance A possible relation between the Rcs phosphorelay and acid resistance emerged from the observation that rcsA , the gene encoding the accessory cofactor of the response-regulator RcsB , was directly regulated by GadE ( Hommais et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore activation of gadAB expression and acid resistance absolutely requires both GadE and RcsB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , it was previously suggested that both RcsB and GadE are required for glutamate-dependent acid resistance via the activation of rcsA expression by GadE , leading to induction of RcsB activity ( Castanie-Cornet et al. , 2007 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both RcsB and GadE are required for activation of gadABC expression The expression of gadE from pGadE strongly stimulates the transcription of gadA and gadBC operons in the wild-type background , as expected from previous reports ( Table 3a , MPC295 and 297 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of GadE , basal activity of RcsB stimulates the expression of gadA/BC , whereas activation of RcsB leads to general repression of the gad genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>Any of these hypotheses might then explain the reported activation of rcsA expression by GadE that leads to the activation of RcsB activity , and consequently , via a feedback loop , to the repression of the gad genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>This demonstrates the ability of RcsBD56E , mimicking phosphorylated RcsB , to interact with GadE forming an RcsB-P/GadE complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding activities of RcsB and GadE at the gadA promoter The afinity of the RcsB/GadE heterodimer for GAD box was estimated by EMSA with increasing concentrations of RcsB in reactions containing a saturating concentration of GadE ( 2.5 mM ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the afinity of RcsB for the RcsB box is very low , several orders of magnitude below that of the RcsB/GadE heterodimer for the GAD box , suggesting that the basal level of RcsB is more eficiently oriented to the activation of the gadA/BC expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>Importantly , we demonstrate here that RcsB and GadE both bind to the GAD box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , activation of gadA transcription requires a GAD box and binding of an RcsB/GadE heterodimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>RcsB is a critical partner of GadE and the binding of both regulators as a heterodimer to the GAD box activates gadA transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , in the presence of MBP-GadE , the addition of 3 or 30 nM of ( His ) 6-RcsB ( Figure 1 , lanes 7 and 8 , respectively ) strongly stimulated gadA transcription ( up to 7-fold ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>At higher concentrations of ( His ) 6-RcsB , stimulation of gadA transcription by RcsB in the presence of GadE declined , essentially disappearing at 3 mM RcsB ( Figure 1 , lane 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been reported that GadE , the response-regulator of RcsB , and RcsB act directly and synergistically to activate gadA transcription ( Castanié - Cornet et al. 2007 , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23274360" target="_blank">23274360</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result therefore indicates that GadE and RcsB act synergistically to stimulate transcription of gadA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we demonstrate through in vitro assays that RcsB and GadE act directly and synergistically to activate gadA transcription ( Figure 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
