<li>GadE binds speciﬁcally to the 20 bp GAD box .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>It should be recalled that the primary activator GadE binds as a classical class I activator at the so-called GAD box , centered at position 62.5 relative to the gadA and gadBC transcriptional start site ( 19 ) ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16980449" target="_blank">16980449</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE binds to the gadE box located 63 bp upstream of the gadA and gadBC transcriptional initiation sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE binds to a 20-bp sequence called the GAD box centered 63 bp from the transcriptional start sites of gadA and gadBC ( 3 , 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>The critical activator of the gadA and gadBC genes is a LuxR-family regulator called GadE ( formerly YhiE ) , which binds to a 20 bp consensus sequence centred -60 bp from the transcriptional start sites of these genes ( Masuda and Church , 2002 ; Ma et al. , 2003a ; Hommais et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>It should be noted that a GAD box sequence to which GadE can bind is located within the P1 region at -210 to -233 bp relative to the GadE start codon ( Ma et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX binds to the gadE control region Regulators EvgA , YdeO and GadE bind to subfragments of the 798 bp gadE upstream control region ( Ma et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>The black bar in the safA promoter represents the inverted-repeat for EvgA binding , gray bars in the iraM , hdeA , and gadW promoters represent PhoP boxes , and white bars in the gadA , hdeA , and gadB promoters represent GadE boxes FIG. 5 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21193607" target="_blank">21193607</a>]<br></li>
<li>No consensus sequence for the binding of GadE on DNA could be identiﬁed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE binding sites were discovered in the upstream intergenic sequences shown to bind GadE ( Fig. 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>Open and gray bars indicate EvgA and GadE binding sites , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19352034" target="_blank">19352034</a>]<br></li>
				</ul></div><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by GadE</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>Expression of the P2 -- lacZ and P3 -- lacZ fusions were unaffected by the presence of GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is not clear why the rpoN deletion was suppressed by GadE under low pH ( Fig. 6C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>It might not be the suppression of the rpoN deletion by GadE , but rather the induction of arrS via the system in panel A by GadE overexpression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE induced by YdeO stimulated the transcription of hdeAB-yhiD , hdeD , gadAX , gadCB , mdtEF , gadW , and yhiM as well as those previously reported promoters [ 9,34,35 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375160" target="_blank">25375160</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although P1 -- lacZ was somewhat affected by an mnmE mutation , that effect was due to the absence of MnmE-dependent synthesis of GadE , which is required for P1 expression ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since gadC is required for acid resistance in pH 2.5 spent EG and GadE is required to induce gadC , the gadE mutant also died quickly under this condition ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17259322" target="_blank">17259322</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both RcsB and GadE are required for activation of gadABC expression The expression of gadE from pGadE strongly stimulates the transcription of gadA and gadBC operons in the wild-type background , as expected from previous reports ( Table 3a , MPC295 and 297 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , expression of the wildtype gadA/B -- lacZ fusions was also lower in the rcsB background and was also unaffected by the overproduction of GadE ( Table 3a , MPC303 and 305 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>As for gadA , gadB , hdeA , and hdeD , no transcripts were detected in the evgS1 gadE strain ( Fig. 2C lane 6 ) , indicating that their expression was GadE dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19352034" target="_blank">19352034</a>]<br></li>
<li>As GadE is also required for stationary phase expression of gadA/BC We demonstrated previously that either GadX or GadW was required by stationary phase cells to express gadA / BC ( Ma et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is required for stationary phase expression of gadA/BC and , when overexpressed , will suppress the gadXW requirement in LB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>We report that the LuxR-like regulator GadE ( formerly YhiE ) is required for expression of gadA and gadBC regardless of media or growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 2A and B ( lanes 1 and 2 versus 3 and 4 ) shows that cells grown to exponential phase in minimal glucose media required GadE ( YhiE ) for acid-induced expression of gadA and gadBC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 4 shows that GadX was highly expressed in a crp gadW mutant ( Fig. 4B ) but that GadE remained essential for gadA/BC expression ( Fig. 4A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore activation of gadA/BC expression by GadE requires both the GadE box and a functional rcsB allele .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under these growth conditions , the GadE activator is primarily implicated in gadA and gadBC transcription ( its overexpression causes GAD production even in cells lacking both GadX and GadW regulators ) , and gadE itself turns out to be acid-induced ( 14 , 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nevertheless , since the in vivo data presented indicate that GadX and GadW activate gadE , and that GadE is essential for gadA and gadBC induction , it seemed possible that the in vivo roles of GadX and GadW in inducing gadA and gadBC may have more to do with their triggering the expression of GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>At least under certain conditions , the regulators GadX and GadW seem to play opposite roles in the expression of gadA , gadBC , and the hde genes , whereas GadE seems to be an essential activator for these genes ( 27 , 43 , 44 , 47 , 66 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716429" target="_blank">15716429</a>]<br></li>
<li>At present , it is known that the expression of the essential regulator GadE , a LuxR-like protein that is encoded by the gadE gene and located in the AFI ( Fig. 1 ) , is under the control of three different activation circuits ( for review , see Foster , 2004 ) : ( i ) the EvgAS/YdeO-dependent circuit activates gadE during the exponential phase of growth in minimal medium ( pH 5.5 ) containing glucose and relies on the activity of both the EvgAS two-component system and the activator YdeO , a member of the AraC/XylS family of transcriptional regulators , ( ii ) the TrmE-dependent circuit activates gadE in the stationary phase in unbuffered LB medium containing glucose and relies on the activity of TrmE , an Era-like molecular switch GTPase , and ( iii ) the GadX/GadW-dependent circuit is required for gadE activation upon entry into the stationary phase in buffered LB medium and involves the transcriptional regulators GadX and GadW , the genes of which are located downstream of gadA and gadX respectively ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>RcsB-dependent regulation of gadABC is not mediated by the regulation of gadEWX genes The expression of gadA and gadBC is regulated by a complex network involving notably the GadE , GadW and GadX regulators ( Ma et al. , 2003 ; see Foster , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of the gadAXW and gadBC operons varies , depending on the culture medium , growth phase and environmental pH. The balance of three transcription factors , GadE , GadX and GadW , is involved in this complex regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17919280" target="_blank">17919280</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE , GadX and YdeO differentially affect the expression of individual gadE promoters Plasmids expressing the E. coli-speciﬁc gadE , gadX and ydeO genes were then introduced into the Salmonella strains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>Intriguingly , two genes encoding cooperative transcriptional regulators , GadX ( yhiX ) and GadE ( yhiE ) , are severely repressed ; it is known that high expression of these genes leads to increased resist-ance of E. coli strains under high acid conditions ( supplemental Table III ) ( 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16418169" target="_blank">16418169</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that the safA promoter drives expression of both safA ( also called b1500 ) and ydeO ( 20 ) ; SafA activates the PhoPQ system in response to acid , and YdeO directly activates GadE expression as well as the expression of several other acid resistance genes ( 9 -- 11 , 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21571995" target="_blank">21571995</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , continuous expression of gadA , gadBC , and the hde genes is likely necessary to cope with permanent acid stress ; this requires continuously high expression of GadE , probably mediated by the EvgSA/YdeO pathway .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716429" target="_blank">15716429</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since GadE controls the expression of numerous genes besides gadA and gadBC , the relevance of these regulatory circuits extends beyond acid resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is the key activator of gadA and gadBC genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was found that RcsB and GadE upregulate , at the similar level , newly identified genes involved in acid stress resistance pathways dependent on glutamate ( yhiM and aslB ) , but these two regulators did not affect the expression of regulatory genes , cadC and adiY ( Table 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21034467" target="_blank">21034467</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was found that RcsB and GadE , at similar levels , upregulated genes involved in acid stress resistance pathways dependent on glutamate ( gadA , gadBC , slp-dctR , hdeAB , hdeD and gltBD ) , arginine ( adiA , adiC ) and lysine ( cadBA ) , but these two regulators did not affect expression of dps ( Table 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of this system is primarily subject to the control of the acid resistance regulator GadE in the gadE-mdtEF operon ( Masuda and Church , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of glutamate-dependent acid resistance genes is induced at low pH and is subject to regulation by GadE , GadW , GadX , TrmE , HNS , TorR , Crp , YdeO , the EvgSA two-component regulatory system and the sigma factor RpoS ( reviewed in Foster 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17273855" target="_blank">17273855</a>]<br></li>
<li>The role of S , GadX , and GadE in the expression of acid resistance genes under different stress conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716429" target="_blank">15716429</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of the corresponding genes is controlled by GadE , the central activator of glutamate-dependent acid resistance ( GDAR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , GadE was able to bind to a fragment of the gadE promoter ( Table 2 ) , suggesting that this gene is autoregulated ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is autoregulated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similarly , the complex regulation of the acid stress response gene gadA , which is activated by GadE and RcsB , involves repression by H-NS ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20952573" target="_blank">20952573</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results verify an earlier gene array study suggesting that GadE might autoregulate expression ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>Neither RcsB nor GadE controlled hdfR regulatory gene expression ( data not shown ) , suggesting that the hdfR is not the target of RcsB-P/GadE complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21034467" target="_blank">21034467</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this regulatory complex , GadE might be the limiting factor , as gadE gene expression is induced 10-fold in the hns-deﬁcient strain , while only RcsD-dependent phosphorylation of RcsB is affected .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20435136" target="_blank">20435136</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , once expressed , it appears that GadE can repress expression from the two farthest upstream promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been reported that EvgA also directly induces GadE expression , forming a branched pathway of regulation ( 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17998538" target="_blank">17998538</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conditional expression of GadE from pQEyhiE ( gadE ) was induced by adding 1.5 mM IPTG to the media containing 100 mg carbenicillin before inoculation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>An evgA-lacZ fusion gene was then constructed to examine whether this operon was also under acid control and whether YdeO or GadE affected expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results indicated that evgAS is not acid induced and is not subject to autoinduction and that neither YdeO nor GadE had any major effect on evgA expression ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>The gadX promoter , which is not activated by GadE or ( unlike all the above promoters ) by induction via EvgA but does require RpoS for induction by low pH ( 1 ) , also showed signiﬁcantly reduced acid-induced expression in the rcsB strain ( Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21571995" target="_blank">21571995</a>]<br></li>
<li>ArcA-P activated gadE expression produces GadE , which activates the transcription from the P1 promoter and further up-regulate the gadE-mdtEF expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>The level of GadE increased in the YY5002 harboring the YdeO-expression plasmid , supporting the prediction that the gadE gene is under the direct and positive control of YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375160" target="_blank">25375160</a>]<br></li>
<li>The yehX gene was induced by the YdeO-expression plasmid in both the parent strain and the gadE mutant but the osmF and yehY genes , and parts of osmF-yehYXW transcription unit , were not induced in the gadE mutant ( Fig. 6 and Table 1 ) , implying that GadE activates the known promoters located at the upstream of yehX which is possibly activated by YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375160" target="_blank">25375160</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data presented in Fig. 4 indicate that GadE does help activate its own expression ( Fig. 4 , compare EF1244 and EF1247 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>The GAD boxes in both of those control regions are essential for expression of the downstream gene and bind pu-riﬁed GadE protein in EMSA experiments ( 3 , 13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>We predicted that this activation occurs by inducing expression of the essential activator gadE and tested the proposed linear EvgA-YdeO-GadE regulatory scheme under physiological conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , it is not clear what purpose this regulation serves in vivo since several studies have shown that EvgA can activate the gadE promoter in a ydeO mutant .24,26 GadE directly activates its own expression while repressing production of YdeO .24 Many structural genes within the AFI , as well as the gadBC locus , are activated directly by GadE , although effectors such as slp appear not to be under GadE control .15,18,27 The contribution of the alternate general stress and stationary phase sigma factor RpoS may also have a role under low pH inducing conditions , since GadE positive feedback can be further supported by its presence .28 The homologous transcription factors * Corresponding author .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20603130" target="_blank">20603130</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA-binding properties of GadE As mentioned in Table 3 , the overexpression of gadE signiﬁcantly induced the expression of genes that are involved in ( i ) the bacterial acid response ( gadA , gadX ) , ( ii ) other stress responses or that encode chaperones ( hdeA , osmC ) , ( iii ) the biosynthesis of bacterial membranes ( ompC , rcsA , rfaG ) and ( iv ) the biosynthesis of glutamate ( gltD ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that overexpression of either GadX or GadE alone , in an FB8 genetic background , is not sufﬁcient to induce expression of genes involved in the bacterial response to low pH when cells are grown at neutral pH. Overexpression of gadX signiﬁcantly induced the expression of 48 genes of the H-NS regulon ( Table 3a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>This could argue that both regulators have a role in cell adaptation to low pH. Under low pH conditions 30 and 19 genes were induced by overexpression of gadX and gadE , respectively , and 18 genes were induced by both regulators ( GadX and GadE ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , the rest of the 30 up-regulated genes forming 21 transcription units were induced in the wild-type but not in the gadE-deficient mutant ( Table 1 ) , indicating that these 21 transcription units are under the direct control of GadE but the indirect control of YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25375160" target="_blank">25375160</a>]<br></li>
<li>0218 * Gene names in bold type are genes induced by both GadE and GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in contrast to other highly low-pH-responsive E. coli genes , asr does not appear to depend on the hierarchical control exerted by the EvgA/S two-component system and the downstream GadE , GadX and GadW regulatory proteins [ 8,35 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15313253" target="_blank">15313253</a>]<br></li>
<li>Reduced S dependence and even a lack of induction upon acid shift is especially pronounced for the regulator GadE ( Fig. 5 ; Table S3 in the supplemental material ) , and the corresponding regulatory pattern of the downstream target genes may be a reﬂection of this change in gadE control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716429" target="_blank">15716429</a>]<br></li>
<li>This generates a feed-forward loop in which the target genes gadA and gadB and probably others are under both direct and indirect control of GadX ( the latter via GadE ) ( Fig. 5C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15716429" target="_blank">15716429</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was reported that transcription from the gadE P3 promoter is negatively regulated by GadE ( Ma et al. 2004 ; Sayed & Foster 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE is an essential transcription factor within the GDAR system , and its expression is increased by acidic stimuli ( Tucker et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24600026" target="_blank">24600026</a>]<br></li>
<li>When using the -222 / +121 gadX : : lacZ construct , which contains the entire gadX 5 ′ regulatory region ( Tramonti et al. , 2002 ; Giangrossi et al. , 2005 ) , we observed that the transcription of the gadX gene from its native promoter increases in the stationary phase but is not appreciably affected by the pH of the growth medium or any of the known regulators of the GadX/GadW-dependent circuit of activation in the gad system , such as GadX , GadW , GadE and RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data from the gadX : : lacZ transcriptional fusions indicate that transcription of the gadX gene from its own promoter is not signiﬁcantly affected by either the pH of the growth medium or any of the regulators of the gad system , such as GadX itself , GadW , GadE and RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under acidic conditions , ArrS expression is induced independently of GadE during the exponential growth phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24600026" target="_blank">24600026</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of arrS has been shown to be dependent on GadE in the early stationary phase as in Fig. 4A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of arrS typically occurs during the stationary growth phase and is dependent upon the factors s and GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24600026" target="_blank">24600026</a>]<br></li>
<li>The arrS is transcribed from its own promoter depending on GadE and RpoS in the early stationary phase and on RpoN and RpoS by acid stimuli in the exponential growth phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcription of 6H57 was dependent on GadE in the early stationary phase and not under the acidic condition in the exponential growth phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501346" target="_blank">21501346</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of arrS is strongly induced during the stationary growth phase , particularly under acidic conditions , and transcription is dependent on sS and GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24600026" target="_blank">24600026</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among its various targets , it regulates in opposite directions the flagella-dependent motility and the acid stress resistance [ 1 ] ; the first via the control of flhDC master flagellar operon by acting both directly and indirectly via regulators HdfR and RcsB [ 2-6 ] ; the second by repressing the genes involved in three amino acid decarboxylase systems , dependent on glutamate , lysine and arginine , via the RcsB-P/GadE regulatory complex [ 6 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21034467" target="_blank">21034467</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION DIFFERENT REGULATORY CIRCUITS ON THE EXPRESSION OF THE gadE-mdtEF OPERON UNDER DIFFERENT PHYSIOLOGICAL CONDITIONS Owing to the important roles of GadE and MdtEF in acid resistance and drug efﬂux respectively in E. coli , transcriptional regulation of the gadE-mdtEF operon under various of growth phases and conditions has been extensively investigated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>No effect of this mutation was observed ( Fig. 1a ) , indicating that the requirement for RcsB in acid resistance is not mediated by RcsA and that under these experimental conditions , the regulation of rcsA by GadE is not pertinent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul></div><br>
